&gt; I know what you mean Misty - it does seem that
&gt; interpretations are often varied.  I am thinking that the
&gt; best way to make progress is to get an audio sample that you
&gt; think is most representative of a given approach&#39;s
&gt; effectiveness, and send that privately to several people. 
&gt; Name the file something innocuous (like File1) and
&gt; don&#39;;t tell the people you send it to what you think you
&gt; hear.  Also, ask the people not to discuss the file with
&gt; anyone else, and have them send what they think they hear
&gt; directly back to you,rather than posting the results in a
&gt; forum or group.
&gt; 
&gt; I think that kind of test is helpful, since it seems to me
&gt; that once someone tells me what the audio clip sounds like,
&gt; then it&#39;s hard for me to hear anything else in it. 
&gt; But,that could be influencing my interpretation (like
&gt; someone pointing to a cloud, telling me its a horse, and
&gt; then I have trouble NOT seeing a horse) ,so it&#39;s better
&gt; to listen before it is suggested to me what i should be
&gt; hearing.
&gt; 
&gt; This way, I think the most progress can be made, because if
&gt; people just keep confirming what we think we hear, and it
&gt; turns out it&#39;s just noise that we are forcing an
&gt; interpretation into, we won&#39;t be making progress (though
&gt; it might make us feel good to believe that we&#39;re being
&gt; successful).  Getting negative feedback to one&#39;s
&gt; approach is not as fun, and might feel like some
&gt; non-believer is trying to debunk us.  But, really, that can
&gt; be the best feedback for progress, since it helps us to
&gt; change tactics when our current approach is not effective,
&gt; rather than continuing down an ineffective path, getting
&gt; accolades from friends, but missing out on other paths that
&gt; might show more promise,.
